------------------------------------------------------------------------
Description:
------------------------------------------------------------------------
This project implements "snush", a minimal but realistic interactive
Unix shell supporting process execution, I/O redirection, pipelines,
signal handling, and background job control.

------------------------------------------------------------------------
Implemented Features:
------------------------------------------------------------------------

1. Interactive Operation
   - Prints "% " prompt and reads user input in a loop.
   - Performs lexical analysis, syntax checking, and command execution.
   - Terminates gracefully on Ctrl-d (EOF) or the "exit" built-in.

2. Built-in Commands
   - cd [dir] : Changes the working directory to dir, or to $HOME if
     dir is omitted. Executed in the parent process (no fork) so that
     the directory change takes effect in the shell itself.
   - exit : Terminates the shell with exit status 0. Also executed in
     the parent process without forking.
   - When a built-in appears inside a pipeline (e.g., "cd /tmp | ls"),
     it runs in a forked child without execvp, so its side effects do
     not propagate to the parent shell.

3. Process Execution (fork_exec)
   - Forks a child process, sets its own process group (setpgid),
     restores default signal dispositions in the child, builds the
     argument array, and calls execvp.
   - Uses a pipe-based synchronization (sync_pipe) to ensure the
     parent registers the job in the job manager before the child
     calls execvp. The child blocks on read(sync_pipe) until the
     parent closes the write end after add_job().

4. Pipelines (iter_pipe_fork_exec)
   - Supports multi-stage pipelines (e.g., "cmd1 | cmd2 | cmd3").
   - All processes in a pipeline share the same process group ID (PGID),
     set to the PID of the first child.
   - Pipe file descriptors are properly duplicated and closed in both
     parent and child processes.
   - A single sync_pipe ensures all children wait until the parent
     has registered the entire pipeline as one job before executing.

5. I/O Redirection
   - Input redirection (<) : Opens the specified file as read-only and
     redirects STDIN_FILENO via dup2. Prints an error if the file does
     not exist.
   - Output redirection (>) : Opens/creates the specified file with
     O_WRONLY | O_CREAT | O_TRUNC and redirects STDOUT_FILENO via dup2.
     Creates the file if it does not exist; truncates if it does.
   - Multiple redirections of the same type are detected and rejected
     during syntax analysis.

6. Signal Handling
   - SIGINT (Ctrl-C) : The shell's sigint_handler sets a volatile
     sig_atomic_t flag. handle_sigint() checks this flag and sends
     SIGINT to the foreground job's entire process group via killpg.
     The shell itself does not terminate.
   - SIGCHLD : The shell's sigchld_handler sets a flag. handle_sigchld()
     reaps terminated children with waitpid(WNOHANG) and decrements
     remaining_processes in the corresponding job. For background jobs,
     when all processes finish, bg_done is set to 1.
   - SIGQUIT, SIGTSTP, SIGTTOU, SIGTTIN are all set to SIG_IGN in the
     parent shell.
   - Child processes restore all signals to SIG_DFL via
     setup_child_signals() before calling execvp.
   - Signal handlers only set flags (no printf inside handlers) to
     maintain async-signal-safety.

7. Race Condition Prevention
   - SIGCHLD is blocked (sigprocmask SIG_BLOCK) before fork() and
     unblocked after the job is registered in the job manager. This
     prevents the race where a child terminates before the parent
     has added the job.
   - setpgid() is called in both parent and child to avoid a race
     between the two.
   - A pipe-based rendezvous mechanism guarantees the child does not
     call execvp until the parent has completed add_job().

8. [Extra Credit] Background Process Execution (&)
   - Commands ending with '&' run in the background.
   - Background jobs are registered in the job manager with state
     BACKGROUND and announced via print_job().
   - SIGCHLD handler asynchronously reaps background processes and
     marks completed jobs (bg_done = 1).
   - check_bg_status() is called at the top of the main loop to
     print completion messages ("Done") and remove finished background
     jobs from the job manager.
   - Foreground wait (wait_fg) is skipped for background jobs.

------------------------------------------------------------------------
Design Decisions:
------------------------------------------------------------------------
- Job IDs are assigned as monotonically increasing unique integers
  (max(existing JIDs) + 1), starting from 1, matching sample_snush.
- The job manager uses a fixed-capacity array (MAX_JOBS = 16) with
  shifting on deletion to keep jobs contiguous.
- Each job tracks up to MAX_PROCS_PER_JOB (64) PIDs.
- wait_fg() uses waitpid(-pgid, ...) to wait specifically for
  processes in the foreground job's process group, properly handling
  EINTR from signals.

------------------------------------------------------------------------
File Structure:
------------------------------------------------------------------------
- snush.c    : Main shell loop, signal initialization, cleanup
- execute.c  : Process execution, pipe/redirection, signal handling,
               fork_exec, iter_pipe_fork_exec, wait_fg
- execute.h  : Header for execute module
- job.c      : Job manager implementation (add, find, remove, delete)
- job.h      : Job data structures and API declarations
- lexsyn.c   : Lexical analyzer and syntax checker
- lexsyn.h   : Header for lexsyn module
- token.c    : Token creation and management
- token.h    : Token type definitions
- dynarray.c : Dynamic array ADT implementation
- dynarray.h : Dynamic array ADT interface
- util.c     : Utility functions (error printing, etc.)
- util.h     : Header for util module
- Makefile   : Build rules using gcc800

------------------------------------------------------------------------
Known Bugs:
------------------------------------------------------------------------
None known. All features have been tested against sample_snush and
produce matching output for the provided test cases.

------------------------------------------------------------------------
Testing:
------------------------------------------------------------------------
Tested with the cases in snush_sample_test_cases.md, including:
- Simple commands: ls, echo, /bin/echo
- Built-in commands: cd, exit, cd with no argument
- Pipelines: ls | cat, ls | head -3, cat < input | grep pattern
- I/O redirection: cat < input.txt, echo hello > out.txt
- Background execution: sleep 3 &, sleep 2 & followed by ls
- Signal handling: Ctrl-C during foreground processes
- Error cases: invalid commands, multiple redirections, syntax errors

------------------------------------------------------------------------
AI Tools Used:
------------------------------------------------------------------------
Used AI coding assistant (Gemini) for the following purposes:

1. Debugging Race Conditions
   - Identified a non-deterministic bug where child processes could
     call execvp before the parent registered the job in the job
     manager. AI suggested implementing a pipe-based rendezvous
     (sync_pipe) mechanism to synchronize parent and child.

2. Signal Handling Design
   - Received guidance on async-signal-safe practices: using
     volatile sig_atomic_t flags in signal handlers instead of
     calling printf directly, and deferring actual processing to
     handle_sigchld() and handle_sigint() in the main loop.
   - Advice on blocking SIGCHLD around critical sections (fork
     through add_job) to prevent race conditions.

3. Background Job Management
   - AI assisted in designing the bg_done flag approach and the
     check_bg_status() polling mechanism in the main loop for
     printing background job completion messages.

4. Code Review and Debugging
   - AI helped review the overall implementation for correctness,
     including verifying proper file descriptor cleanup in pipeline
     stages and ensuring setpgid() is called in both parent and
     child to avoid PGID races.

5. README Writing
   - AI assisted in writing this detailed readme document.
